The last point I want to make is if you feel the change in directorship from Norton to Porter changed your job?
Well, I think that Dr. Porter has a long-range vision.
He's looking more to the national scene.
He has given us some more challenges.
I'm used to dancing with more freedom to do what you want to do.
And that's what we did.
And I still offer it a lot.

We've got to get back to remembering that this is Texas United.
United we stand.
We must be together.
We must work for the common good.
Everybody.

We are .

Is there anything else you'd like to add about your experiences with TEAS?
Well, TEAS, in my view, is a fine organization.
It's an organization designed to help people who want to develop themselves and their students.

If there are people who do not want to promote Texas A&M and its students, then let them get out of the way unless a tease is oriented to helping solve problems of importance to the industries and the people of Texas.
And part of that problem is making sure that the kids of our state get the right kind of education.
And that means getting the right kind of professional development.
Again, they should be involved in research.
We can help them do that.
So I'm just saying that these priorities, they can all work honestly in a dedicated way.
